# Project Memory Instructions

This project uses AgentMemory via MCP for cross-session memory.

## Available Memory Tools

When the `agent-memory` MCP server is connected, you have these tools:

- `memory_recall` — Always call this at the start of a session with the user's first message to load relevant context
- `memory_add` — Store important facts, decisions, preferences, and project context
- `memory_search` — Search with filters (category, entity, status)
- `memory_forget` — Archive outdated memories
- `memory_timeline` — View history of changes for an entity
- `memory_stats` — Check memory store health

## When to Store Memories

Store a memory when the user:
- States a preference ("I prefer tabs over spaces")
- Makes a decision ("We're using PostgreSQL for this project")
- Shares context ("The API is deployed on AWS us-east-1")
- Completes a milestone ("Auth system is done and tested")
- Reports a bug pattern ("The flaky test is in test_auth.py")

## When to Recall Memories

- At the start of every session, recall with the user's first message
- When the user references past decisions or context
- Before making architectural recommendations
- When the user asks "do you remember..."

## Memory Categories

Use these categories for consistency:
- `preference` — User coding style, tool choices, communication preferences
- `project` — Architecture decisions, deployment config, tech stack
- `technical` — Bug patterns, performance notes, API details
- `career` — Role, company, team info
- `personal` — Name, timezone, communication style
- `general` — Anything else
